Try using VSURF

Make df of just the predictor variables I want to include

xdf <- df %>% 
  select(Elevation,
         Slope.Deg,
         Aspect.rad.fold.NESW,
         heatload,
         incidrad,
         Year,
         Years,
         BasDia2016.cm, 
         Ht_cm,
         shrubarea1,

         shrubarea3,
         Cov1, 
         Cov1.2, 
         Cov1.3, 
         Ht1, 
         Ht1.2, 
         Ht1.3,
         ShrubSpp01, 
         ShrubSpp02, 
         ShrubSpp03
         )

Normalize the numeric ones

normalize <- function(x) {
    return ((x - mean(x)) / sd(x))
  }
xdf <- xdf %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, normalize)

STOP HERE TO SAVE TIME

See how correlated they are

ggplot(df, aes(x = shrubarea3, y = shrubarea2))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "loess")

Run a random forest

forest <- randomForest(x = xdf %>% select(Ht_cm, Years, shrubarea3, shrubarea2, Ht1.3, BasDia2016.cm, Year, heatload, incidrad, ShrubSpp03), y = df$VertGrowth_Rel, importance = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
varImpPlot(forest)

Delete SHRUBAREA3 and HEATLOAD based on the results of the above randomforest

xdf <- xdf %>% 
  select(-shrubarea3, -heatload)

Look at a linear model using the variables that were identified by VSURF, plus interactions that seem biologically meaningful

Structure data for LM

LMdf <- df %>% 
  mutate(sqrt_shrubarea2 = sqrt(shrubarea2)) %>% 
  select(Sdlg, VertGrowth_Rel, Years, Ht_cm, shrubarea2, sqrt_shrubarea2, Ht1.3, BasDia2016.cm, incidrad, ShrubSpp03, Year) %>% 
 mutate_if(is.numeric, normalize)
LMdf <- droplevels(LMdf)

See whether model with shrubarea3 or sqrt_shrubarea3 is better

AIC(lme(VertGrowth_Rel ~ Years + Ht_cm + shrubarea2 + Ht1.3 + BasDia2016.cm + incidrad + ShrubSpp03,
        data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Sdlg, method = "ML"))

Look at individual effects

Note: the plots look exactly the same but with different axes if you dont normalize the numeric predictors. So for including plots to visualize in the paper, I just use non-normalized data

Re-run model with non-normalized data

LMdf <- df %>% 
  select(Sdlg, VertGrowth_Rel, Years, Ht_cm, shrubarea2, Ht1.3, BasDia2016.cm, incidrad, ShrubSpp03) %>% 
  mutate(shrubarea2 = shrubarea2/10000)
LMdf <- droplevels(LMdf)

Re-create effects plot using predictorEffects() and ggplot

eff_shrubarea <- predictorEffect("shrubarea2", LM)
effects_df <- as.data.frame(eff_shrubarea)
ggplot(effects_df)+
  geom_line(aes(x = shrubarea2, y = fit))+
  geom_ribbon(aes(x = shrubarea2, ymin = lower, ymax = upper), alpha = .5, fill = "#fdbb84")+
  theme_bw()+
  xlab(bquote('Shrub cross-sectional area ' (m^2)))+
  ylab("Predicted relative growth (cm/cm)")+
  ggtitle("Pine growth in relation to shrub environment within 2 m")+
  geom_rug(data = df, aes(x = shrubarea2/10000, y = VertGrowth_Rel), alpha = .5, position = "jitter", sides = "b")+
  ylim(c(-0.02,0.25))

ggsave(file = "../../results/figures/FireFootprints/PineVertRel.png")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

Residuals

E <- resid(LM, type = "normalized")
df$E <- E
pred <- predict(LM)
plot(LM)

plot(df$shrubarea2, E)

plot(df$Ht_cm, E)

plot(df$Years, E)

plot(df$Ht1.3, E)

plot(df$BasDia2016.cm, E)

plot(df$incidrad, E)

plot(df$Year, E)

ggplot(df, aes(x = log(df$shrubarea3), y = E))+
  geom_point()+
